    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm looking at my student loan amortization table and i'm confused. i've been making the same monthly payment for a year now but the principal balance is barely moving. why is the balance decreasing so slowly even though i'm paying the same amount every month?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "This is a common point of confusion, and it's usually because of how amortization works, which is often more aggressive than it seems at first. In the early stages of a loan, a larger portion of your fixed monthly payment goes towards interest, and only a smaller portion actually chips away at the principal balance. It can feel like you're just paying the interest, but trust me, the principal *is* decreasing, just at a slower pace initially. If you want to speed things up, you might consider making extra payments, which would be entirely dedicated to the principal.",
